olence together enables appreciation of the full significance of Jesus' consistent disassociation of revolutionary violence from his words and deeds. The book thus articulates an understanding of Jesus' nonviolence that is firmly rooted in the historical context of Second Temple Judaism, presenting a challenge to the "seditious Jesus hypothesis"-the claim that the historical Jesus was sympathetic to revolutionary ideals. Jesus' rejection of violence ought to be understood as an integral component of his eschatological vision, embodying and enacting his understanding of (i) how God's kingdom would come, and (ii) what would identify those who belonged to it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aHistorical Jesus.  aJesus and Violence.  aJewish Eschatology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2021z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z978311075377608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishz978311075419308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021z9783110753974oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107038700 cprintz978311070241540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311070377140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110703771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110703771.jpg  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Ebook Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075072-0  DG Ebook Package English 2021b2021  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 